---
import LabLayout from '../../layouts/LabLayout.astro';
const base = import.meta.env.BASE_URL;
---

<LabLayout title="Lab 1: FPGA and MCU Setup and Testing" labNum={1} githubUrl="https://github.com/juliacygong/E155/tree/main/lab01">
  <section>
    <h2>Introduction</h2>
    <p>
      In Lab 1, a <a href="https://hmc-e155.github.io/assets/doc/E155%20Development%20Board%20Schematic.pdf" target="_blank" rel="noopener">development board</a> containing
      a FPGA (UPduino v3.1) and MCU (mikroBUS_Socket) was soldered together. The objective was to program
      the FPGA with Verilog code that responds to 4 input DIP switches and outputs a specific seven segment
      display as well as three LED displays. Other learning outcomes included soldering, testing, and debugging
      circuits and Verilog.
    </p>

    <h2>FPGA Design and Testing Methodology</h2>
    <p>
      The following tables establish the relationship between the various inputs and outputs on the development board.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab1/lab1_table1.png`} alt="Table of inputs and outputs" />
      <figcaption>Figure 1: Inputs and outputs required in the FPGA design.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab1/lab1_table2.png`} alt="DIP switch to LED mapping" />
      <figcaption>Figure 2: Relationship between DIP switch inputs and LED outputs.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The design was developed using a clock divider, boolean algebra, and multiplexers. The clock divider creates
      the 2.4Hz oscillating LED, boolean algebra selects between DIP switch signals to determine other LED outputs,
      and multiplexers select the corresponding segment outputs for the 7-segment display. The 7-segment display
      shows all hexadecimal digits distinctly.
    </p>
    <p>
      The 7-segment display has a common anode — the cathode must be grounded to turn on an LED. Therefore the
      Verilog sends <code>0</code> to turn on a segment and <code>1</code> to turn off a segment.
    </p>

    <h3>Hardware Implementation</h3>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab1/board.jpg`} alt="Completed development board" />
      <figcaption>Figure 3: The completed development board.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab1/breadboard.png`} alt="Breadboard layout" />
      <figcaption>Figure 4: Physical breadboard layout of the 7-segment display.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <p>
      The resistors used in the 7-segment display were determined by looking at the segment luminous intensity
      and voltage drop in the datasheet. The desired current is 10mA and the voltage drop per segment is 2.1V.
      With a 3.3V supply: V = 3.3V − 2.1V = 1.2V → R = 120Ω. I used 220Ω resistors to ensure appropriate
      current draw.
    </p>

    <h2>Technical Documentation</h2>
    <p>
      Source code is in my <a href="https://github.com/juliacygong/E155/tree/main/lab01" target="_blank" rel="noopener">GitHub repository</a>.
      It contains two Verilog modules, 2 testbenches, and 2 testvector files.
    </p>

    <h3>Block Diagram</h3>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab1/lab1_blockdiagram.jpeg`} alt="Block diagram" />
      <figcaption>Figure 5: Block diagram for the two Verilog modules.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h3>Schematic</h3>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab1/lab1_schematic.jpeg`} alt="Schematic" />
      <figcaption>Figure 6: Schematic for the FPGA and 7-segment display.</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>Results and Discussion</h2>
    <p>
      Results were verified using an automatic testbench simulation on Questa and an oscilloscope trace to
      verify the LED oscillating frequency.
    </p>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab1/lab1_waveforms.png`} alt="Testbench waveforms" />
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab1/lab1_results.png`} alt="Testbench results" />
      <figcaption>Figure 7: Testbench simulation results from Questa. All 16 tests passed with no errors.</figcaption>
    </figure>
    <figure>
      <img src={`${base}images/labs/lab1/lab1_oscilloscope.JPG`} alt="Oscilloscope trace" />
      <figcaption>Figure 8: Oscilloscope trace of the LED at 2.4Hz (measured frequency matches desired).</figcaption>
    </figure>

    <h2>Conclusion</h2>
    <p>
      The design meets all lab requirements. The development board is fully assembled and all outputs
      for the 7-segment display and LEDs match expected outputs. All hexadecimal digits display uniquely
      and each segment has the same brightness.
    </p>
    <p>
      I spent a total of 15 hours on this lab. A large portion was spent soldering and learning
      the Lattice Radiant environment. A useful tip: learn how to navigate the "FTDI Error" that
      occurs when trying to program the FPGA — the lab description could have mentioned this.
    </p>

    <h2>AI Prototype Summary</h2>
    <p>
      Prompt given to ChatGPT: <em>Write SystemVerilog HDL to leverage the internal high speed oscillator
      in the Lattice UP5K FPGA and blink an LED at 2 Hz.</em>
    </p>
    <p>
      The generated code included several unnecessary local parameters and the logic could be
      simplified. With more specific guidance, ChatGPT produced better code in a follow-up prompt.
      Full transcript: <a href="https://chatgpt.com/share/68b7add1-90c8-800e-8b15-9c966d711eab" target="_blank" rel="noopener">chatgpt.com/share/…</a>
    </p>
  </section>
</LabLayout>
